ck Americans in the Western US and show modern rodeo riders—who still compete on today’s circuit—as “descendants” in a more than two-hundred-year lineage of Black cowboys. A gorgeous tribute to the ropers and riders—legends like Willie Thomas, Myrtis Dightman, Rufus Green, Bailey’s Prairie Kid, Archie Wycoff, and Calvin Greeley—as well as the secretaries, judges, and pick-up men and even the audience members who were as much family as fans, Juneteenth Rodeo ultimately seeks to put Black cowboys and cowgirls where they have always belonged: in the center of the frame.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican American cowboyszTexasxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aAfrican American rodeo performerszTexasxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aJuneteenthzTexasxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aMinorities in rodeoszTexasxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aRodeoszTexasxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh  aPhotography, African-American, Black rodeo, Black cowboys, Texas, Juneteenth, Rufus Green, Myrtis Dightman, African American history.1 aPearson, Demetrius W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Demetrius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32954240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477329559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477329559/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles